  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Submitting a Vague or Generic Business Plan</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">France evaluates the viability and benefit of your project carefully. A generic "consulting services" or "import/export" plan without specific clients, market analysis, or financial projections will be rejected. Your business plan should demonstrate clear understanding of the French market, realistic revenue projections, and how you'll create value or jobs. Invest in professional business plan development if needed.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating the French Language Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While not officially mandatory for the visa, French language proficiency is increasingly expected for business success. Government offices, banks, and many business partners operate in French. Start learning before you apply, and be prepared for interviews in French at some consulates. For permanent residence and citizenship, French language tests are required.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Having Documents Properly Translated</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">All non-French documents must be translated by a sworn translator (traducteur assermenté). Regular translations are not accepted. This includes your business plan, diplomas, criminal record certificate, and any supporting documents. Budget time and money for professional sworn translations—rushing this causes delays.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting to Validate Your Visa with OFII</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After arriving in France, you must validate your visa online with OFII within 3 months. This is not optional—failing to validate can invalidate your residence rights and cause problems at renewal. Set a reminder immediately upon arrival. The process requires paying €200 and may include a medical examination.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Treating It Like a Passive Golden Visa</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">France's entrepreneur visa requires genuine business activity—not just parking money. At renewal, you'll need to show your business is operational: bank statements, tax filings, employee records if applicable. If your business has failed, explain what happened and your plans going forward. Authorities check that you're actually running a business, not just holding a visa.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in France -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in France</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      France consistently ranks as having one of the world's best healthcare systems. As an entrepreneur, you'll initially rely on private insurance but can transition to the French social security system once your business is established and you're paying contributions.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">The French Healthcare System</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The French system combines public insurance (Sécurité Sociale) with private supplementary insurance (mutuelle). The public system covers approximately 70% of costs; most French residents have a mutuelle to cover the remainder.
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Public Healthcare (After Establishment)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>• World-class hospitals and specialists</li>
          <li>• Generous coverage (70% of costs)</li>
          <li>• Prescription medications heavily subsidized</li>
          <li>• Free preventive care and screenings</li>
          <li>• Access to any doctor (no gatekeeping)</li>
          <li>• Excellent maternal/child health services</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Private Insurance Benefits</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• Immediate coverage (no waiting period)</li>
          <li>• 100% cost coverage with good plan</li>
          <li>• Private rooms in hospitals</li>
          <li>• Dental and optical coverage (limited in public)</li>
          <li>• English-speaking services available</li>
          <li>• International coverage for business travel</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Accessing the French System as an Entrepreneur</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Your path to French healthcare depends on your business structure:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Auto-entrepreneur / Micro-entrepreneur:</strong> Pay simplified social contributions to URSSAF; covered by Sécurité Sociale des Indépendants (SSI)</li>
      <li><strong>SARL manager (gérant majoritaire):</strong> Travailleur Non Salarié (TNS) status; SSI coverage</li>
      <li><strong>SAS president:</strong> Assimilé salarié status with salary; covered by general CPAM regime</li>
      <li><strong>Timeline:</strong> Typically 3-6 months after business registration to receive carte vitale</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Major Cities Healthcare Infrastructure</h3>

