  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak French to get a Passeport Talent?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          French is not officially required for the visa application, but it's increasingly expected for business success. Some consulates may conduct interviews in French. More importantly, daily business operations, government interactions, and banking often require French. Plan to learn—it will improve your experience significantly. For permanent residence and citizenship, French language tests are mandatory.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family work in France with the Passeport Talent - Famille?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Your spouse receives "Passeport Talent - Famille" status with full work rights—they can be employed, start their own business, or freelance without restrictions. Children can attend school (public or private) and later work when of legal age. This is a significant advantage over many other visa categories where family work rights are limited.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if my business fails?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Business failure doesn't automatically invalidate your visa, but you'll need to address it at renewal. Options include: starting a new business, transitioning to employment (change of status), or demonstrating ongoing entrepreneurial activity. France understands that businesses can fail—what matters is your genuine entrepreneurial intent. However, repeatedly failing to establish viable businesses may affect renewals.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can apply for permanent residence or citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Permanent residence (carte de résident) is available after 5 years of continuous legal residence. Citizenship is also possible after 5 years, but requires French language proficiency (B1 level minimum), integration into French society, and passing a civics test. Continuous residence and stable financial situation are important factors. Some applicants receive citizenship faster through exceptional contributions to France.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I travel freely in Europe with the Passeport Talent?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. The Passeport Talent grants residence in France and free travel within the 26 Schengen countries for up to 90 days in any 180-day period. You can visit clients, attend conferences, and conduct business across Europe without additional visas. However, you cannot relocate your primary residence to another EU country—your main base must remain France.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between Passeport Talent and the regular entrepreneur visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Passeport Talent offers significant advantages: 4-year visa from the start (vs. 1-year for regular entrepreneur), automatic family inclusion with work rights, and a more streamlined process for qualified applicants. The regular entrepreneur/profession libérale visa has lower barriers but requires annual renewals and family members must apply separately. Choose Passeport Talent if you meet the qualifications (degree or experience) and capital requirements.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      France's Passeport Talent offers a compelling pathway for entrepreneurs and investors who want to actively build businesses in Europe's second-largest economy. Unlike passive golden visas, France rewards genuine entrepreneurial activity with one of the most favorable visa structures available: a 4-year multi-year permit, automatic family inclusion with work rights, and relatively accessible capital requirements.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The €30,000 Business Creation threshold is significantly lower than Spain's €500,000 or Portugal's €500,000—but you must have a real business plan, not just capital to park. France wants innovators, job creators, and entrepreneurs who will contribute to the economy. The application scrutinizes your business viability, not just your bank balance.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For investors with €300,000+, the Economic Investor track offers a path to French residence through meaningful capital deployment. And for executives expanding existing businesses, the Company Representative track provides the smoothest approval process of all.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        France's entrepreneur and investor visas are ideal for those who want to actively participate in Europe's economy—not passively hold assets. The La French Tech ecosystem, strong investor incentives, and access to the EU market make France particularly attractive for tech startups and innovation-driven businesses. Budget €30,000-40,000 minimum to launch (Business Creation track), plus €200-450/month for comprehensive health insurance. French language skills will significantly improve your experience and business success.
      </p>
